-- Copper Leads Gains in Base Metals as China’s PMI Beats Estimates
-- B y   B l o o m b e r g   N e w s
-- 2013-09-02T01:46:22Z
-- http://www.bloomberg.com/news/2013-09-02/copper-leads-gains-in-base-metals-as-china-s-pmi-beats-estimates.html
Copper led gains in industrial
metals after a gauge of manufacturing in  China , the biggest
consumer of commodities, rose to a 16-month high.  Metal for delivery in three months on the London Metal
Exchange climbed as much as 1.8 percent to $7,230.25 a metric
ton, the biggest gain since Aug. 22. It traded at $7,225 at 9:25
a.m. in  Shanghai  and rose 3.2 percent last month.  China’s manufacturing purchasing managers’ index, the
official government measure, rose to 51 in August, beating the
median economist estimate and rising from 50.3 in July. A
separate PMI index compiled by HSBC Holdings Plc and Markit
Economics is set for release at 9:45 a.m. local time. after
initial figures showed the biggest jump in three years for
China.  “Metals were encouraged by the PMI reading,” said Fang Junfeng, an analyst at Shanghai CIFCO Futures Co., adding that
the momentum will strengthen if the HSBC and Markit PMI data
beats estimates.  Expanding Chinese manufacturing may reinforce an outlook
that the economy is responding to Premier  Li Keqiang ’s policies
to support growth. JPMorgan Chase & Co. yesterday raised
estimates for an increase in Chinese gross domestic product,
citing continued strength in infrastructure and real-estate plus
a pickup in exports.  Futures for delivery in December on the Shanghai Futures
Exchange rose 0.9 percent to 52,410  yuan  ($8,563) a ton. Metal
for delivery in December advanced 1.8 percent to $3.2925 a pound
on the Comex in  New York .  On the LME, aluminum, zinc, nickel and lead rose. Tin fell.  To contact Bloomberg News staff for this story:
